<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / International Company News: BellSouth in novel telecoms plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BELLSOUTH, the Baby Bell regional telephone company serving south-eastern
US, yesterday announced an unusual plan to allow outside parties to attach
new telecommunications services to its advanced computer-based network.
US telecommunications companies usually deny outsiders access to their
computer networks and BellSouth, the largest of the Baby Bells, claimed
yesterday that it was the first to propose 'significant opening of its
reservoir of advanced technologies to other service developers'.
The plan provides further evidence of the rapid convergence of the
telecommunications, computer and media industries and the decline of the
monopolies enjoyed by US local telephone companies.
Under the BellSouth plan, customers and developers of enhanced
telecommunications services would be able to plug in to the company's
Advanced Intelligent Network, the telecommunications industry's equivalent
of a computer's basic operating software.
Mr Duane Ackerman, president of BellSouth telecommunications, said the move
would spur the development of new services, such a voice recognition and
personalised telephone numbers which followed individuals wherever they
went.
'Doubtless we'll create competition for some of our own advanced services,'
he said. 'However, our extensive research clearly indicates that increased
growth of our network by our own customers, coupled with usage growth
generated by new enhanced service providers, will increase our AIN revenues
overall.'
The company stressed that the plug-in capability would not allow an outsider
to delve deeply into the network and compromise the integrity of the
network.
BellSouth filed its plan yesterday with the Federal Communications
Commission, the government agency which oversees the industry and must first
approve the proposal.
</TEXT>
