<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / International Company News: Indonesian timber group plans
Dollars 200m flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BARITO Pacific Timber, one of the world's largest wood products companies,
plans to go public with a Dollars 200m share offer that values the company
at about Dollars 2bn.
The company, which will float later this year, is the flagship of the Barito
Pacific Group led by Mr Prajogo Pangestu.
BPT has banking, real estate and petrochemical subsidiaries, as well as
2.46m hectares in timber concessions of its own and access to a total of 5m
hectares. This latter figure represents almost 8 per cent of Indonesia's
natural production forests.
The company, set up in 1976, estimates its assets at Dollars 1bn, although
this excludes the full value of forestry concessions which, under Indonesian
law, remain the state's property.
Last year BPT recorded a gross profit of Dollars 114m on sales of Dollars
380m. For 1993 the company forecasts sales of Dollars 599m and a gross
profit of Dollars 309m. Although exact figures are not available, company
documents show first-quarter sales this year of nearly Dollars 90m and a
gross profit of about Dollars 50m.
The surge in profits will result, company officials say, from a
restructuring of debt, estimated at Dollars 560m, and a sharp increase in
the world price of timber. BPT exports 95 per cent of production to Japan
and Taiwan.
The company also confirmed it had recently made a private placement of
shares, amounting to a 20 per cent stake, to Taspen, the largest state
pension fund.
While Indonesia, with the third largest natural forests in the world after
Brazil and Zaire, has a competitive advantage in wood products, brokers
attribute BPT's growth in part to Mr Pangestu's political connections.
Bankers say it was Mr Pangestu who in 1990 helped cover losses of Dollars
419m suffered by Bank Duta, majority-owned by three charitable foundations
chaired by President Suharto.
</TEXT>
