<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Losses in US mar Dixons' UK gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROWING losses and closure costs at the Silo chain in the US pushed down
annual pre-tax profits at Dixons, the UK's largest electrical retailer, to
Pounds 33.5m from a restated Pounds 50.1m.
The losses, which overshadowed an encouraging performance by Dixons' UK
chains, will increase pressure on the group to find a way of turning Silo
around or make further closures. Dixons' share price fell 15p to 195p.
Operating losses at Silo increased from Pounds 16.9m to Pounds 22.4m. Dixons
shut five more stores on top of the 45 closures announced in January, and
will close a further 11 this year, leading to an exceptional provision of
Pounds 36.2m.
Without the provision for Silo, a Pounds 6m write-down on UK properties  - a
business discontinued last year - and a Pounds 1m loss on disposals, the
profit before tax in the year to May 1 would have been Pounds 76.7m, broadly
in line with analysts' forecasts. Group turnover increased to Pounds 1.93bn
from Pounds 1.81bn.
Mr John Clare, managing director, said sales at Silo had risen 2 per cent in
the second half, after a 3 per cent fall in the first half, and sales had
increased year-on-year in many areas of the US. However, those increases
were outweighed by a decline in its biggest markets, especially in
California.
'Success in the UK chains has been hidden and frittered away by the US
losses,' one analyst said yesterday.
In the UK retail business, operating profits rose to Pounds 77.6m from
Pounds 71.9m. Stripping out a Pounds 10m warranty fund surplus from last
year's figure, profits improved 25 per cent.
UK turnover rose 10 per cent to Pounds 1.32bn, while the electrical market
grew 4 per cent. Like-for-like sales jumped 15 per cent in Currys
out-of-town superstores, 8 per cent in Currys high street stores, and 6 per
cent in Dixons.
But Dixons warned that while gross margins had been maintained for the third
year running, increasing price competition had led to pressure on margins in
the current year, although like-for-like sales continued to be ahead.
The European property division also increased its operating profit from
Pounds 5.4m to Pounds 11.4m, after selling several properties, mainly in
Belgium, and letting out the Beaulieu office development in Brussels to the
European Commission.
Dixons ended up with a post-tax loss, after an exceptional taxation charge
of Pounds 20.6m, relating to a liability to pay US retirement medical
benefits - a hangover from the acquisition of Cyclops, Silo's parent
company, in 1987. That led to a loss per share of 6.5p, compared with 6.5p
earnings last year.
A slightly increased final dividend of 4.6p, paid out of reserves, makes a
total of 6.2p, up from 6p.
Lex, Page 26; Details, Page 29
</TEXT>
