<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Germans advise Budgens on trial discount stores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUDGENS, the small food retailing chain, will open four trial discount
stores next month in a format it devised with Rewe, one of Germany's largest
food retailers.
Rewe is a private company which operates 8,000 stores and has 15 per cent of
the German food market. In April it stepped up the continental European
assault on the discount end of British retailing through buying a 26 per
cent stake in Budgens.
Budgens is converting four of its existing 100 stores in the south-east of
England to the new format, named Penny Market. Rewe currently operates more
than 1,400 discount grocery outlets, as well as supermarkets and
hypermarkets.
Several continental European discounters, attracted by the high profit
margins available in UK food retailing, have opened stores in the past three
years, making discounting the fastest-growing area of the market.
Budgens will decide whether to expand the new format after two months. Mr
John von Spreckelsen, chief executive, said that if more Penny Market stores
were opened, they would be in addition to the Budgens chain. No decision had
been made on how any expansion would be funded.
Mr von Spreckelsen, a German who was installed as chief executive of the
struggling chain in 1991, meanwhile confirmed that the recovery in Budgens'
profitability was continuing, in spite of what he described as 'continuing
attrition' from retail competitors.
Last year 800,000 sq ft of competitive space was opened close to Budgens'
outlets in the south-east, which themselves total only 600,000 sq ft, and
another 700,000 sq ft of competitive space will be opened in the current
year.
Pre-tax profits rose by 33 per cent to Pounds 6.2m in the year to April 25,
although turnover fell marginally from Pounds 291m to Pounds 285m. The board
is recommending a return to the dividend list with a payment of 1p.
Earnings per share dipped from 3.5p to 3.4p, partly because non-trading
items incurred a cost of Pounds 250,000 from the closure of unprofitable
outlets, compared with profits of Pounds 842,000 in the previous year.
