<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lawson urges independent Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HANDING responsibility for monetary policy to the Bank of England would lead
to lower interest rates and strengthen the accountability of bank officials,
Lord Lawson, the former chancellor, said yesterday.
Lord Lawson told the Treasury and Civil Service committee that the present
system under which which politicians controlled interest rates led to
international investors demanding a 'risk premium' when buying sterling and
threatened the UK's anti-inflation credentials.
However, Lord Lawson's views were opposed by Lord Healey, a former Labour
chancellor, who told the committee he was 'an agnostic veering towards
scepticism' on the need for an independent bank.
Mr Kenneth Clarke is to make his first appearance as chancellor before the
Treasury and Civil Service committee on July 21.
</TEXT>
