<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Hope of accord on block vote
recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPPORTUNITIES for comp-romise between the Labour party and the unions over
internal party democracy appeared to recede yesterday as Mr John Smith, the
Labour leader, reaffirmed his commitment at the annual conference of the
Transport and General Workers Union to the 'simple principle' of
one-member-one-vote.
Mr Smith told the conference that the principle must apply to the selection
of parliamentary candidates, but side-stepped the issue of union involvement
in the election of the party's leadership.
Mr Smith last week indicated that he would consider a deal which allowed the
continued participation of unions in an electoral college for the selection
of leader.
Such a compromise was flatly rejected by Mr Bill Morris, TGWU general
secretary, speaking yesterday after Mr Smith's address. 'I don't think that
we are in the business of trading off one part of our members' democratic
rights for another,' he said.
The GMB, another of the large unions opposed to the Labour leadership's
plans, has already made known its rejection of the deal.
The scene now looks set for a damaging split between the two wings of the
party at Labour's autumn conference. Unless Mr Smith can drive a wedge
between the unions opposed to reform, he faces a defeat: unions control 70
per cent of the votes at Labour's conference.
Mr Smith told the TGWU conference that there was 'no question of breaking
the historic links' between Labour and the unions. He added, however: 'We
should not be afraid of modernising our relationship.'
The word 'modernise' was greeted by a few shouts of 'rubbish' from the
audience, although, overall, the Labour leader's speech was well received by
the 700 delegates. Mr Morris said afterwards that he did not think Mr
Smith's speech had 'changed many minds in the conference'. One delegate said
the Labour leader should remember 'the trade unions started Labour, not the
other way round'. The union is likely to vote overwhelmingly today for a
motion against reducing trade union input into Labour's decision-making
procedures.
Referring to a scheme which would offer cut-price party membership to trade
unionists who paid the political levy, Mr Smith appealed for union members
to join the party as full individual members.
This was not just the democratic way forward, but would be a 'new source of
energy and strength', he said.
Mr Morris said later: 'We must not confuse proposals to increase Labour
party membership with the rights of trade unions within the Labour party
constitution.'
</TEXT>
