<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Private cash sought for 30% of CrossRail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT hopes that private investors will fund at least 30 per cent
of the cost of the CrossRail project to build two tunnels under central
London.
Ministers anticipate a public contribution of between Pounds 800m and Pounds
1.2bn, leaving a possible 60 per cent of funding for the Pounds 2bn scheme
to be raised from the private sector.
But they believe moves to revamp inflexible design and project-management
procedures could conceivably shave Pounds 300m off the final price-tag. This
could leave just Pounds 500m for the private sector to make up.
CrossRail would enable passengers travelling on suburban trains into British
Rail's Paddington and Liverpool Street stations to reach the West End and
the City without having to change to the Underground system.
It is central London's biggest public transport project since the Victoria
line opened in 1968.
Ministers hope to be able to inject competition by asking potential
investors how much financing they would be prepared to provide, given
certain fixed assumptions about future fare levels.
They indicate that the size of the public contribution would be based on
quantifying the project's wider benefits such as reduced traffic congestion
and other environmental benefits.
One possible source of private funding which is under consideration by
ministers is a new London transport trust that would draw its income from a
levy on businesses - perhaps in the form of a business rate increase.
A penny on the business rate in greater London would raise more than Pounds
100m - enough by some estimates to support about Pounds 1bn in bond issues.
Ministers see an opportunity for introducing such a levy relatively
painlessly following the 1995 rating revaluation. This is expected to see
the burden of business rates shift away from the south-east towards the
Midlands. By some estimates, the rates bills of offices in the City could
more than halve.
The timing could fit neatly with CrossRail which is thought to be at least
18 months away from full clearance, following last month's second reading of
the parliamentary bill needed for it to go ahead.
The government's drive to attract private finance to projects such as
CrossRail is motivated by the urgent need to modernise the country's
infrastructure at a time when the spiralling public sector borrowing
requirement is forcing it to crack down on public spending.
London First, the business-led initiative set up last year to promote
strategic thinking about the capital, estimates that more than Pounds 17bn
will be needed over the next 10 years to fund the renewal of London's rail
and underground systems and to finance new projects.
Current government investment plans will provide only half of what is needed
over the next five years.
During last month's second reading debate Mr Steven Norris, transport
minister for London, said the government wanted the private sector
'fundamentally' involved in CrossRail. He said the government was not
contemplating a project to which the private sector 'might merely make a
small contribution'.
</TEXT>
