<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Guidelines on selection of pupils by ability are eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHOOLS will be allowed to accept up to 10 per cent of their intake on the
basis of specific abilities under guidelines released yesterday by the
Department for Education.
Mr Robin Squire, the new education minister, announced that schools which
are strong in art, drama, music, sport or technology will be allowed to
select up to 10 per cent based on pupils' ability or aptitude in these
fields.
The education department said: 'A measure of specialisation does not mean
selection, which implies choice by the school; instead it means increased
choice for parents and pupils.'
The inclusion of technology, which is an academic subject within the
national curriculum, brought claims that other subjects could be added to
the list if the government wished to encourage selection.
Mrs Ann Taylor, Labour's education spokeswoman, described 'specialisation'
as a code-word for 'selection'.
The department said admissions policies should be 'clear, reasonable and
objective'.
Mr Squire refused to offer encouragement to schools wishing to become
grammar schools despite a ruling last week that appeared to show that
schools which had opted out of local authority control could make this
change without difficulty.
He said no conclusions should be drawn from the court decision that Mr John
Patten, the education secretary, acted correctly in allowing a school in
Penrith, Cumbria, to become selective, even though local consultation had
resulted in 55 formal objections to the proposal and only one letter of
support.
The ruling was justified because the governors supported the proposals, and
they were regarded as representatives of their community, the education
department said.
Under the new guidelines, any school whose character would be changed by
selecting pupils on academic criteria will have to undergo a period of
statutory consultation.
</TEXT>
