<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Sheehy defends proposals for police shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIXED-TERM contracts for police officers would not be a question of trying
to squeeze the public sector into a private-sector mould, Sir Patrick
Sheehy, chairman of the government-appointed inquiry into police and pay
responsibilities, said yesterday.
The introduction of fixed terms - with officers appointed on initial 10-year
contracts subsequently renewable every five years - is the committee's most
controversial recommendation. Sir Patrick, chairman of BAT Industries,
mounted a determined argument in favour of it when he addressed the
Association of Chief Police Officers conference in Birmingham yesterday.
In his speech he called on the government to 'move ahead with implementation
of our proposals as rapidly as possible'.
He said the present police tenure arrangements amounted to telling the
taxpayer that, whatever the changing needs and circumstances, the service
could do nothing to alter its staffing and skill profile in less than 30 or
40 years. He said: 'Surely this is unacceptable. The police service needs
the opportunity to renew itself.'
The committee made a series of recommendations which it believes would sweep
away barriers to effective management. They would place a duty on managers
to recruit carefully, plan ahead and introduce adequate career development
and training arrangements.
Sir Patrick defended the other most controversial proposal, to introduce
performance-related pay. No organisation could afford to employ 'passengers
or mere figureheads' and he said he made no apology for proposing that
senior officers' pay should be particularly dependent on their
responsibilities.
Sir Patrick faced critical questioning from senior officers and local
authority representatives at the conference.
Mr Keith Povey, chief constable of Leicestershire, said the service had been
attracting high-quality recruits and needed to continue doing so. He
questioned how the recommendations for lower starting rates, loss of housing
allowance, increasing the service requirement for full pensions from 30
years to 40 years, raising the retirement age to 60 and fixed-term contracts
would improve recruitment.
Mr Richard Wells, chief constable of South Yorkshire, said comments by Sir
Patrick had implied that his proposals would be supported by progressive
people in the police service. He added: 'There are progressive people in the
police service who actually welcome change who might want to question some
of your recommendations.'
</TEXT>
