FT  08 JUL 93 / Crown Estate payment rises by 8.4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CROWN ESTATE, the property owned by the sovereign, who surrenders its
profits to parliament in exchange for the civil list, yesterday announced
that its payment to the exchequer had risen by 8.4 per cent to Pounds 75.9m
for the year to end of March.
The estate, the UK's largest landowner, generated a revenue surplus of
Pounds 74.3m, up 3.6 per cent. Its value had fallen by 6.8 per cent to
Pounds 1.66bn by the year-end.
Lord Mansfield, the estate's first commissioner, said the estate had
'weathered the recession very well'.
The estate said its strength reflected 'the wide-ranging nature and quality'
of its portfolio, and 'the effect of good financial management and a prudent
investment strategy'.
Lord Mansfield said the Leasehold Enfranchisement Bill going through
parliament would have 'a considerable effect' on the estate.
Although the estate is immune from the bill's provisions, it has agreed to
enfranchise leaseholders except in places such as Windsor, Regent's Park and
Kensington, where there are historic associations, special security
considerations or close connections with royal palaces and parks. In these
cases, tenants will be allowed to extend their leases to 150 years.
</TEXT>
