<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / GKN calls for economic stability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR David Lees, chairman and chief executive of industrial group GKN,
yesterday urged the government to provide a more stable economic climate for
business, and to make permanent the 40 per cent first-year capital allowance
introduced for one year only in the Autumn Statement, John Griffiths writes.
He told the Commons trade and industry committee that the UK had suffered
two significant recessions in little more than a decade, unlike most
competitor countries. This had made it considerably more difficult for
productivity improvements to be made.
Sir David said that in productivity terms, GKN's UK facilities were still
bottom of the league table of its European plants, but were 'catching up
quickly'. He acknowledged, however, that it would take a further three to
five years before they were likely to match GKN's best continental European
plants.
He described as overstated a widespread view that the City and financial
institutions were preoccupied with the short term.
Sir David's plea for greater stability and extra support for business by
extending the capital allowances on plant and machinery was supported by
executives of the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders.
It also called on the government not to allow sterling to strengthen
significantly.
</TEXT>
