<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Tec chiefs vote today on central body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNDREDS of directors of Training and Enterprise Councils will today decide
whether they want a strong central representative body, on the lines of the
Confederation of British Industry.
The vote, which is at the heart of how the 82 Tecs in England and Wales see
themselves, will be held at their third annual conference, at the National
Exhibition Centre in Birmingham.
Tecs, which are employer-led, administer more than Pounds 2bn of public
funds on government-funded training programmes. They also seek to improve
the training of people in work and stimulate economic development.
Agreement in principle is likely to be given at the conference to a new
national body, called the National Tec Council, which will replace the much
criticised G10, the group of 10 Tec chairmen that represents common concerns
to the government.
Directors will then debate how powerful the new council should be. Some Tec
directors, most of whom are senior business leaders, believe that Tecs have
insufficient say with the government and want an authoritative lobbying
body.
Others believe that if such a body was created they would lose their local
autonomy - the key ingredient to which some Tecs attribute their growing
success.
A small but vociferous group of directors is against any diminution of their
direct contact with the government. They are likely to support the
appointment of a part-time chairman and annual budget of around Pounds
500,000. Others want a full-time director-general backed by a strong
secretariat.
After the vote there will be keynote speeches by three secretaries of state
 -whose attendance, along with several junior ministers, indicates the
important the government gives to Tecs.
An important and controversial theme at the conference will be the priority
that most Tecs place on economic development - rather than running the
publicly-funded training schemes for the unemployed and Youth Training, the
scheme for young people.
Tecs argue that unless they are able to help create enterprises there will
be fewer jobs.
They are likely to be pleased by the new employment secretary, Mr David
Hunt, who is expected to tell them that he sees them as prime movers in
economic development.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
