<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Carsberg backs Law Society move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR BRYAN CARSBERG, director-general of fair trading, yesterday signalled
his approval of the Law Society's latest application for wider advocacy
rights for solicitors in the higher courts.
Sir Bryan said the application - which was rejected by the Lord Chancellor's
Advisory Committee last week - did not have, nor was likely to have, the
effect of restricting, distorting or preventing competition to any
significant extent.
The liberalising nature of the proposals would serve to lower entry barriers
to the market for the supply of higher court advocacy services, he said.
But in his advice on whether to approve the society's application, Sir Bryan
said that Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, should consider a mandatory
requirement that a solicitor's advice to a client on choice of advocate, the
likely costs and the criteria for any recommendation, should be clearly set
out in writing.
Sir Bryan said that extending higher court advocacy rights to solicitors
would widen consumer choice and might lead to gains in efficiency.
His advice will now be considered by Lord Mackay together with the advice of
his Advisory Committee before he decides whether the society's application
should be approved.
</TEXT>
