<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / World Trade News: Murdoch threat to close NY Post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RUPERT Murdoch, who has been managing the troubled New York Post since
March 29 with the aim of eventually buying it, is threatening to close the
tabloid tomorrow if he cannot reach agreement by then with its unions on
cost-cutting measures.
Mr Murdoch's News Corporation is running New York's smallest and raciest
tabloid under a deal with the bankruptcy court which controls the Post's
fate.
The agreement, which runs until the end of August, gives him permission to
walk away from the management contract, after a three-day notice period, if
he and the paper's 11 unions cannot agree on terms which would make the Post
economically viable.
On Tuesday, Mr Murdoch gave the court the required three-day notice of
intention to end the contract at 4pm on Friday.
A spokesman for News Corporation said the Post was losing about Dollars
330,000 (Pounds 220,000) a week and Mr Murdoch had spent some Dollars 8m
since he emerged in late March as a potential saviour for the paper.
Union officials have said that while they are prepared to make some
concessions, Mr Murdoch has been asking for too much. News Corporation's
pressure on the unions follows a June 29 ruling by the Federal
Communications Commission, the government agency which oversees the media
industry, allowing him to own both the Post and a television station in New
York.
Federal regulations normally forbid ownership of both a paper and TV station
in the same market, but Mr Murdoch received a waiver after receiving
widespread political support in New York and making clear that he would shut
the paper quickly if he did not receive the green light.
If he backs out of the management contract, the paper's fate would once more
be in the hands of the bankruptcy court, which might be unable to find an
alternative buyer. If Mr Murdoch's talks with the unions succeed, he will
then have to negotiate precise purchase terms with the court.
</TEXT>
