crop of cadets at Sandhurst military academy. Would-be officers up in front
of the army's Regular Commissions Board, which vets all applicants, tended
to be 'less well-prepared' to take on leadership roles than in the past.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, the committee's Tory chairman, blames the schools for
placing too much emphasis on academic qualifications and not enough on
sport. But his colleague, Winston Churchill, will perhaps remember his
grandfather's remark: 'Based on many years' observation, officers with high
athletic qualifications are not usually successful in the higher ranks.'
