<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Kuwait denies Gulf war payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUWAIT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KUWAIT last night dismissed as a fabrication a report that it had paid for
political support from western and Arab countries during the 1990-91 Gulf
crisis, Reuter reports from Kuwait.
Finance Minister Nasser Abdulla al-Rodhan said in a statement that an
allegation in a report in yesterday's Financial Times was devoid of all
truth. 'Kuwait has never resorted to these means at any time, either in the
past or at present,' he said.
The statement carried by the official Kuwait News Agency said the charge was
aimed at tarnishing the country's image and its right to restore its
sovereignty following the 1990 Iraqi invasion.
'He (Mr Rodhan) accused parties deeply implicated in financial
irregularities of spreading such malicious reports in a futile attempt to
clear themselves from the crimes they have committed,' the agency reported.
The Financial Times report said former officials of the Kuwait Investment
Office (KIO) had said Dollars 300m (Pounds 200m) missing from the KIO's
Spanish operation was used to buy western and Arab support to free Kuwait
after Iraq invaded.
The report said large sums were alleged to have been used at the United
Nations to buy votes which later provided the legal basis for Kuwait's
liberation by a multinational force.
A coalition of western, Arab and Asian armies drove Iraqi troops from Kuwait
in February 1991.
Mr Rodhan said the allegations aimed 'at insulting the international will
which was unanimous in denouncing the Iraqi invasion and occupation based on
respect for international legitimacy and the United Nations charter'.
</TEXT>
