<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Party agrees to Nigerian power talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S Social Democratic party (SDP) has agreed in principle to form an
interim national government to replace the military regime on August 27,
provided that it can choose key members of the government and that elected
local, state and legislative institutions remain intact.
The National Republican Convention (NRC) is joining the SDP in talks with
President Ibrahim Babangida on terms agreeable to both parties and the
military government. The NRC would be a more grudging participant,
preferring the option of new elections before August 27.
According to a presidential spokesman on Tuesday, the military government
would dissolve all democratic institutions and possibly the two army-created
parties unless they were ready for fresh elections by the end of July.
The SDP has rejected the option of fresh elections before the military hand
over because they insist that their presidential candidate, Mr Moshood
Abiola, was a fair winner in the June elections. The government has annulled
those polls and banned Mr Abiola from standing in fresh elections. SDP
officials say that the inclusion of Mr Abiola as head of the interim
government is a condition of their acceptance.
'Things have reached a collision course and that would not help the parties,
the military or the people,' said Mr Amos Idakula, spokesman for the SDP.
'We are opting for this because it is the only way to get the military out
of power. This interim government would be a buffer between the outgoing
regime and elected civilian government. Elections held under the military
would have no credibility.'
The civilian protest in Lagos which has paralysed the country's commercial
capital for three days has made clear popular rejection in south-west
Nigeria, the main base of Mr Abiola's support, of fresh elections before
August.
'We would not be fooled by that,' said a Lagos civil servant. 'The June
polls results should be upheld. There is no option being offered by the
government, it is an ultimatum. We could not accept new elections under
them.'
The two parties met in Abuja yesterday and agreed on the need to maintain
elected civilian institutions and to end military rule in August, but the
NRC accuses SDP of intransigence in ruling out elections under the existing
regime.
'We are paying for the sins of the SDP,' said an NRC spokesman in Abuja.
'Our position is that there should be new elections immediately. But if the
SDP show restraint and table proposals which are in the national interest,
we are prepared to negotiate if it will preserve the corporate unity of
Nigeria.'
Soldiers have restored order in Lagos as protesters await details of the
plan for an interim national government.
Mr Uche Chukwumerije, the information minister, denied reports that anyone
had been shot in Lagos. Contrary to local reports, the main casualties on
Tuesday were the result of a road accident in which a taxi driver ran over
some youths in road blockade and was lynched by a crowd.
</TEXT>
