<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Triumphant Milosevic heaps scorn on west
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French president's wife, Mrs Danielle Mitterrand, this week became the
latest international figure to founder on the rock of Serbian intransigence.
She returned to Paris yesterday after failing to persuade President Slobodan
Milosevic to free Mr Vuk Draskovic, the opposition leader beaten by police
during demonstrations in Belgrade last month.
'It would not be the truth to say I am not disappointed. . . . Perhaps we
overestimated our powers of conviction. But I don't believe it was a
failure,' Mrs Mitterrand told reporters.
But snubbing the west and its envoys is a skill which Mr Milosevic exercises
with increasing relish. In a cynical move this week, his cabinet even went
so far as to wish Mrs Mitterrand a 'pleasant stay in Belgrade', at the same
time as ignoring her pleas for Mr Draskovic's release.
With Greater Serbia within his reach, a triumphant Mr Milosevic appears
convinced that the time has come to erase any remnants of opposition to his
rule.
The west's refusal to take action against Serbian forces in Bosnia was a
signal to Mr Milosevic that there would be no international resistance if he
snuffed out the remaining Serbian opposition and independent media. His
earlier promises that Serbia would never bow to western pressure have been
fulfilled.
Flexing his muscles, Mr Milosevic has refused to release Mr Draskovic,
jailed since June 1. He has ignored international appeals on behalf of Mr
Draskovic, including personal letters from Mr John Major, UK prime minister,
and President Francois Mitterrand.
The imprisonment and subsequent beating of the opposition leader and his
wife Danica are an act of personal vengeance by the Serbian president, who
is unwilling to tolerate any challenge to his hold over Serbia.
Last month, he cemented his grip on the remains of Yugoslavia, now
comprising Serbia and its tiny ally Montenegro, when he replaced the federal
president, Mr Dobrica Cosic, with a faithful party apparatchik. Mr Milosevic
now has unlimited power in Serbia. His cronies have been installed at the
head of state institutions and enterprises.
The open and brutal treatment while in police custody of the opposition
leader has sent a clear message to any would-be opponents of the government,
as well as ordinary Serbs, of what might will happen to them if they dare
resist the government.
Belgrade journalists fear Mr Milosevic will soon carry out a purge of the
media which opposed his grip on power. The editor-in-chief of Borba, the
independent Belgrade daily, is likely to be ousted this week.
Mr Milosevic reportedly has a police force of 80,000 available to crush any
protest and to sow the seeds of fear prior to possible social unrest as the
Serbian economy collapses under the weight of war and 14 months of UN
sanctions.
There is no doubt sanctions are taking their toll, but they have had no
effect on moderating Serbia's hardline stance towards the UN and other
international organisations.
Serbia over the past month has ordered the Conference on Security and
Co-operation in Europe to close its Belgrade offices which monitored human
and minority rights. The government also declared as 'unwelcome' the UN
special envoy on human rights and war crimes.
In addition, Serbia has refused to participate in the Geneva conference on
succession in the former Yugoslavia. The unrecognised Yugoslav federation is
also delaying or refusing to issue new visas for incoming western diplomats
and journalists.
Mr Milosevic last week said sanctions would 'not be lifted by pleading or
concessions' to the international community. So far his arrogant resistance
has paid off. By refusing to bend, he appears to have gained the respect of
the west as the main power broker in the Balkans.
But for all his present power the Serbian president knows he is in a race
against time. This winter could find most inhabitants of Belgrade facing
severe heating and food shortages if sanctions continue to be enforced
strictly. Then, even 80,000 police could have trouble containing their
anger.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
