<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / Mackay to advertise for judges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WANTED: judge to sit on northern circuit. Must be prepared to travel and
accept substantial drop in earnings. Knowledge of the law an advantage.
Preferred age 45-55. The Lord Chancellor is an equal opportunities employer.
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, finally bowed to pressure last night in
agreeing to end the secrecy in England's judicial appointments system by
advertising judges' jobs and holding open competitions for specific judicial
posts.
Speaking to a packed house of his judicial brethren at the lord mayor's
annual judges' dinner, Lord Mackay said he still believed he was the best
person to make judicial appointments but, having consulted senior
colleagues, he had decided changes were needed.
His announcement follows complaints from Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief
Justice, of a serious shortage of High Court judges which resulted in the
appointment of an extra 10 in March.
Lord Mackay said he would be putting machinery in place to help in
forecasting the numbers of judges and the expertise required at different
levels.
Specific job descriptions would be drawn up detailing the work involved and
the qualities required. Initially, only jobs up to circuit judge level would
be advertised, but if this experiment worked, the Lord Chancellor would
consider extending it to senior judicial posts.
Lord Mackay said he was anxious to see if there were further measures he
could take to encourage applications by female, black and Asian lawyers.
He would also explore the scope for involving non-lawyers in the selection
process. Lay people with experience in the justice system might be asked to
sit on interview panels.
Lord Williams of Mostyn QC, Labour's legal affairs spokesman in the Lords,
who last year called the current judicial appointments system 'bizarre and
farcical', said he was delighted Lord Mackay had finally seen the force of
the argument for a more open system.
</TEXT>
