<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 93 / British Gas admits pipeline price rises may be too high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS admitted yesterday that it could have got its pipeline charges
wrong and withdrew increases of up to 30 per cent proposed only a month ago.
The admission marks a spectacular U-turn for the company just three weeks
before the Monopolies and Mergers Commission is due to report on the future
of the UK gas industry.
British Gas recently defended the price rises, which ranged from 2 per cent
to 30 per cent and were to be levied on rival suppliers which send gas
through the group's pipelines to industrial customers.
The change of tone has been seen as evidence by some industry observers that
the company is worried about the commission's likely verdict on the gas
industry. The commission could suggest British Gas lose its monopoly over
household gas supply and propose that the group hive off its pipeline
operations. The commission is also due to recommend a rate of return on the
pipeline operations which will affect charges.
The government, which must decide whether to implement any of the
commission's recommendations, is believed to favour the introduction of
competition unless there are very strong arguments against.
It also wants British Gas to make the links between its pipelines division
and its marketing operations clearer. This could be achieved by dividing
them into distinct subsidiaries within the group or by setting them up as
separate concerns.
British Gas said yesterday that it would delay the implementation of the
proposed price rises until October next year while it examines the potential
for cutting them.
Mr Harry Moulson, who takes over next Tuesday as managing director of
British Gas's transportation business, said the group was responding to
pressure from rivals. 'I looked at these price increases and said I don't
believe I can live and fight in this marketplace on this basis,' he said.
He said British Gas would talk with rival suppliers, after which it could
revise the proposed rises. However, it will go ahead with an increase in
October of 3.5 per cent, which is based on inflation and other
considerations.
Mr Norman Ellis, managing director at Kinetica, one of British Gas's main
rivals, said: 'The increases are completely unacceptable whether they are
implemented now or later.' Mr Ellis has made a formal complaint about the
charges to Ofgas, the industry regulator which has challenged the basis of
the price increases and asked the group to justify them.
British Gas said it would publish additional information on its cost base to
justify the price rises.
</TEXT>
