<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Granada active
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Granada underlined its predatory intentions in the television sector with
another move into the market to pick up stock in London Weekend Television.
The catering to leisure group bought a further 4.5m preferred shares in LWT
at 500p each, taking its stake up to 19.99 per cent. The shares crept up a
penny to 483p. Granada slipped 4 to 417p.
Leisure and media analysts were sceptical over press reports that the two
groups were discussing a merger, particularly prior to the government's
expected pronouncements on the very subject, due by the end of the year.
Drugs issues Glaxo and Wellcome shrugged off recent weakness to register
sharp advances. Dealers said the corrections were underpinned by some keen
US buying, as well as a short position undertaken by one of the leading
London marketmakers. Glaxo advanced 14 1/2 to 561 1/2 p. Wellcome gained 13
at 658p.
Confirmation that international conglomerate Lonrho had appointed James
Capel as its joint broker with Strauss Turnbull was seen as another move
helping to elevate the stock to 'blue chip' status in the market. The shares
hardened 2 to 126p. Bargain hunters were seen for English China Clays,
boosting the stock 6 to 411p.
Barclays and National Westminster were the pick of a rather sluggish banking
sector, with both stocks responding to some aggressive buying in the traded
options market and lingering hopes of another cut in domestic interest
rates. Both share prices moved to within 10p of their all-time highs.
NatWest advanced 6 to 487p on turnover of 3m, while a similar figure was
traded in the options market. Barclays rose 4 to 481p on 1.6m dealt. Abbey
National was up 2 at 417p and TSB 3 at 193p.
The sale and subsequent purchase of a block of 2.2m Sedgwick shares failed
to unsettle the stock price, which closed only marginally easier at 200p.
A further rally in crude oil prices helped the oil sector stabilise after
the hefty losses of recent sessions.
The oil team at NatWest Securities said a move by the UN to allow the Iraqis
to sell around Dollars 1.6bn worth of oil, for humanitarian reasons and for
reparations to Kuwait, would entail the sale of 600,000 barrels of oil a
day. 'This is not enough to swamp the market by itself, but probably enough
to prevent prices rising in their normal seasonal pattern in the third
quarter,' said NatWest.
The broker told its clients to pick up oil issues with good recovery
prospects, notably British Petroleum, but warned of the exploration and
production sub-sector's vulnerability to weak crude prices.
BP touched 296p but eased back to close only a fraction ahead at 294p amid
talk of a number of profits downgrades in the pipeline, notably from BZW.
Shell Transport rallied 5 to 616p.
Burmah Castrol rose 6 to 708p, reflecting its wide exposure to the German
economy and hopes of further interest rate cuts in that country.
Among the oil minnows, New London shares closed 2 3/4 off at 5 3/4 p after
the proposed sale of its International Drilling Fluids business to
Schlumberger and the latter's proposed acquisition of a 10 per cent stake in
New London fell through.
Celsis, the medical equipment manufacturer, made an impressive debut in the
market, with its flotation via a placing and offer nearly four times
oversubscribed. The shares, issued at 100p, peaked at 117p before
profit-taking saw them close just a penny ahead at 101p; turnover was a
hefty 9.9m shares.
Turnover in British Steel rose to 9.5m and the shares shed a penny to 88 1/2
p as NatWest Securities reiterated its sell recommendation following a
meeting with the company.
Fears that the current UK defence cutbacks may eventually lead to the UK
government scaling down its order for the new Challenger tank hurt Vickers,
off 2 at 149p.
Westland Group, on the other hand, was cheered by reports that an order for
transport helicopters would not be subject to the proposed defence cuts. The
shares appreciated 7 to 221p.
GKN, which has a near 30 per cent stake in Westland, moved 7 ahead to 460p
on the same sentiment and news of an improvement in UK car sales. Lex also
benefited from the car news and rose 7 to 386p.
Suggestions that Saudi Arabia was about to place a substantial order for
Airbus aircraft, for which British Aerospace builds the wings and holds a 20
per cent stake in the company, boosted BAe. The shares closed 6 up at 392p.
BT performed strongly, finishing 8 higher at 426p with 5.6m shares traded,
after news that the company had received 5.2m registrations for the BT 3
share offer. Dealers said the shares were helped by strong support in the
traded options market, where the equivalent of a further 6.3m shares changed
hands.
Positive talk from Kleinwort Benson was said to have helped Boots shares
climb 6 to 433p. MFI improved 1 1/2 to 131 1/2 p in spite of being
downgraded by Goldman Sachs.
</TEXT>
