FT  07 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Greycoat deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Property shares showed good gains in the wake of the deal agreed by Greycoat
with its main shareholder, Postel, to secure its future. 'It is another sign
that the financiers see a healthy future for the sector,' said one property
analyst.
However, speculative investors in Greycoat, who had piled in to the 9 1/2
per cent preference shares on Monday ahead of the well-publicised
negotiations with Postel and pushed the price up 17 1/4 to 51 3/4 p, saw
most of their gains evaporate. The stock ended 12 3/4 down at 39p, after
34p. The ordinary shares lost 2 at 17p.
Meanwhile, BZW took the opportunity to raise its forecast for average
capital value movements for 1993/94. However, in spite of pent-up investment
demand for 'quality' properties estimated at Pounds 7bn, the broker believes
that property shares will soon enter a period of consolidation. Among the
majors yesterday, MEPC moved ahead 8 to 402p, Hammerson 'A' 9 to 290p, Land
Securities 9 to 585p and British Land 7 to 328p.
