<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities depressed by US
economic fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
INVESTOR skittishness depressed US equity markets yesterday afternoon, with
worries about inflation conspiring with the recent release of disappointing
economic data to leave Wall Street unsettled, writes Patrick Harverson in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average tumbled 34.04 to 3,449.93 and the Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 lost 4.41 at 441.43, while the Nasdaq composite shed 2.27 to
702.22. New York SE volume was 220.7m shares.
Before the afternoon sell-off, prices were trapped in a narrow trading range
throughout the morning, never breaking more than a few points above or below
opening values. Many investors and dealers were reluctant to trade equities
because of doubts about the outlook for the economy and the approaching
second quarter reporting season.
Even strong overseas stock markets, and a morning jump in bond prices, which
sent the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond to a record low of 6.664 per
cent, failed to stimulate buying interest.
Foreign equities were boosted by last week's cut in German interest rates,
while bond prices rose on reports that the poor June jobs figures would
persuade the Federal Reserve to postpone any plans for an inflation-curbing
rise in US rates.
By the afternoon, equity and bond prices moved solidly lower as surging
commodities prices left investors increasingly nervous about inflation. In
late trading the long bond's yield had risen to 6.676 per cent.
General Motors, however, added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 44 1/8 on reports
that Wall Street analysts were turning increasingly bullish on the stock in
the wake of improvements in the company's product line. In the afternoon the
company reported the best sales month ever for its GMC Truck unit. Ford slid
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 48 3/8 and Chrysler eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars
45 5/8 .
Selected technology stocks were hard hit by analysts' downgrades.
Hewlett-Packard dropped Dollars 5 to Dollars 75 1/2 in volume of 2.2m shares
after SoundView Financial lowered its 1993 earnings forecast because of
concern over possible weakness in the printer business.
Tandem Computer fell Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 10 after Morgan Stanley cut
its investment rating from a 'buy' to a 'hold' and lowered its earnings
forecast.
On the Nasdaq market, Apple Computer ended a net Dollars  3/4 lower at
Dollars 37 3/4 after firming in morning trading on news that it plans to
shed 16 per cent of its staff.
Canada
TORONTO posted a small loss in active trading after gold shares rose but
oils continued to decline. The TSE 300 index ended 6.1 off at 3,984.4 and
falls led rises by 412 to 358. Volume swelled to 86.3m shares, the fourth
highest on record.
The golds sector advanced 2.45 per cent as the bullion price jumped
USDollars 6.50 an ounce in New York. The oil and gas index fell 2.2 per
cent.
</TEXT>
