<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Norway calls for correction of
deficiencies in EC regime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY YESTERDAY spelt out a long list of demands on fisheries to the
European Community and pointed out deficiencies in the EC's regime that
would have to be corrected if it was to become a member.
'The outcome of the membership negotiations in this area will play a
decisive role in determining the public attitude on Norwegian accession to
the community,' it warned Brussels officials.
Mr Jan Henry T. Olsen, the anti-EC fisheries minister, reiterated that
Norway had no more fish to give away to the community.
Norway failed to get the backing for EC membership in a 1972 referendum
partly because the community adopted a fisheries policy shortly before it
was going to make the decision to join.
Key issues in the discussions this time include mutual access to waters,
management and conservation, control of quotas and technical regulations,
structural matters, market access and market organisation.
Norway attached the greatest importance to the continuation of its regime
ensuring control and sustainable management of marine resources and
aquaculture activities.
It said recognition by the EC of the fundamental relationship between
Norway's coastal population settlements and fish resources was essential.
Norway demanded arrangements to ensure that fishing quotas remained at the
disposal of member states to which they had been allocated. It attached
particular importance to stringent enforcement of quotas and technical
regulations while insisting that it must be allowed to uphold its own
first-hand sales system.
