<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Economic gloom hits metal
prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GLOOMY economic outlook for most of the world's big industrial countries
was reflected by metals markets yesterday as nickel prices dropped to the
lowest level for 5 1/2 -years, lead fell to a seven-year low and tin slipped
back towards its recent 20-year low.
With most of continental Europe gripped by recession, recovery in Japan
still months away and a far from robust recovery in the US , 'the chances of
a demand-lead boost for metals in the remainder of this year are slim,' said
Mr Angus MacMillan, research manager at Billiton-Enthoven Metals, a
Royal/Dutch Shell subsidiary.
Nickel was also badly affected by a rise in London Metal Exchange stocks
reported yesterday following a steady fall totalling 10,000 tonnes in June.
Traders said a ship carrying between 6,000 and 12,000 tonnes of Russian
nickel had arrived in Europe.
'There is more than enough nickel around to justify a further fall in
price,' said Mr Wiktor Bielski, analyst at Bain &amp; Company, part of the
Deutche Bank Group.
Meanwhile, traders suggested tin for delivery in three months might be on
its way to the Dollars 4,990 a tonne, the 20-year low touched recently.
Lead, suffering from a huge contraction of demand from European and Japanese
car makers, touched Dollars 388 a tonne yesterday before recovering slightly
by the close.
