<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / International Company News: Dublin approves Aer Lingus
rescue plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AER LINGUS, the Irish state airline, last night received the government
approval for its rescue plan which includes the shedding of more than 25 per
cent of the 5,500 workforce and open up the possibility of direct
transatlantic flights between Dublin and the United States.
The cabinet finally gave clearance to the plan despite last-ditch efforts by
the airline's trade unions and supporters of the so-called Shannon stopover
to have it extensively modified.
Mr Brian Cowan, the transport minister, told the Dail (parliament) that the
airline was facing unprecedented losses and that time was running out to
save it.
This year, the air transport division is expected to loseIPounds 64m (Pounds
61m) after registering a loss of IPounds 50m last year.
The government has promised a capital injection of IPounds 175m over the
next three years conditional on union acceptance of the rescue plan.
Mr Bernie Cahill, executive chairman, last night called upon unions to
'respond positively' to the plan, adding: 'The alternative would be to
witness the inexorable decline of Aer Lingus.'
Mr Paul O'Sullivan, the main representative of the trade unions, said,
however, that he was extremely disappointed by the government's endorsement.
Business leaders in the Shannon region of the west of Ireland also expressed
anger at the decision claiming that the ending of the Shannon stopover will
have a severe adverse economic impact on the area.
For the first time direct flights will now become possible between Dublin
and the US, which should attract new carriers to the route.
Mr Cowan said he would open talks shortly with the US aviation authorities
to negotiate a new bilateral agreement covering air transport between the US
and the republic. Aer Lingus at present carries about 500,000 passengers a
year across the Atlantic.
</TEXT>
<XX>
