<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Bonn sacks prosecutor over shooting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE GERMAN government yesterday sacked its chief state prosecutor, Mr
Alexander von Stahl, in a new, and increasingly desperate, move to allay
public disquiet over the shooting of a suspected terrorist.
The action was ordered as confusion continued to surround the precise
circumstances of how Mr Wolfgang Grams, a suspected member of the fanatical
left-wing Red Army Faction, and a member of the government's crack
anti-terrorist unit both died in a shoot-out in eastern Germany.
Mr von Stahl's enforced retirement was ordered by Ms Sabine
Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger, justice minister, following the resignation on
Sunday of Mr Rudolf Seiters, interior minister and a close ally of
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
The latest move was announced as a measure to preserve the dignity of the
federal prosecutor's office from the confusion surrounding the
anti-terrorist operation 10 days ago, in which Mr Grams and the young
policeman were shot dead and Ms Birgit Hogefeld, a suspected faction member,
was arrested.
Instead, the public impression is one of confusion in the highest offices of
state and an inability to allay fears that the suspected terrorist was shot
dead as he lay wounded and disarmed on the ground.
The country's top police investigator, Mr Hans Ludwig Zachert, head of the
federal criminal investigation office, confirmed yesterday that Mr Grams was
probably shot with his own gun, from extremely close range. He was unable to
confirm precisely what had happened at the end of a gun battle with the
elite GSG-9 anti-terrorist unit on the Bad Kleinen railway station near
Schwerin.
Mr von Stahl, a member of the Free Democratic party in the governing
coalition, is a political appointee, and his retirement had to be ordered by
the justice minister.
In a statement issued last night, Ms Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger said that
the importance of the office meant that a prolonged debate over the occupant
would be damaging. She thanked Mr von Stahl for his efforts 'to explain the
terrible events in Bad Kleinen'.
</TEXT>
